    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Race Condition Counter Demonstration</h1>

    <div class="container">
        <!-- Buggy Counter -->
        <div class="widget buggy">
            <h2>Buggy Counter (Race Condition)</h2>
            <div id="buggyCounter" class="counter-display">0</div>
            <button id="buggyButton">Increment (Buggy)</button>
        </div>

        <!-- Corrected Counter -->
        <div class="widget corrected">
            <h2>Corrected Counter (No Race Condition)</h2>
            <div id="correctedCounter" class="counter-display">0</div>
            <button id="correctedButton">Increment (Corrected)</button>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="explanation">
        <h3>Understanding the Race Condition and Its Fix</h3>

        <p>A <strong>race condition</strong> occurs when multiple parts of a program try to access and modify shared data at the same time, and the final outcome depends on the unpredictable order in which these operations complete. In web development, this often happens with asynchronous operations (like network requests, `setTimeout`, or user interactions) that modify a shared state.</p>

        <h3>The Buggy Counter Explained:</h3>
        <p>
            When you rapidly click the "Increment (Buggy)" button, multiple asynchronous `incrementBuggy` calls are initiated. Each call does the following:
            <ol>
                <li><strong>Reads</strong> the current value of `buggyCount`.</li>
                <li>Waits for a simulated delay (`setTimeout`). During this delay, another click might initiate a new `incrementBuggy` call.</li>
                <li><strong>Modifies</strong> the *read value* by adding 1.</li>
                <li><strong>Writes</strong> this new value back to `buggyCount` and updates the display.</li>
            </ol>
            <p><strong>The problem:</strong> If two clicks happen quickly, both might read the *same initial value* before either has a chance to write its updated value. For example:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>`buggyCount` is 0.</li>
                <li>Click 1 starts: reads 0.</li>
                <li>Click 2 starts: reads 0 (before Click 1 has written its result).</li>
                <li>Click 1 finishes delay: calculates 0 + 1 = 1. Writes 1.</li>
                <li>Click 2 finishes delay: calculates 0 + 1 = 1. Writes 1.</li>
            </ul>
            <p>Instead of the count becoming 2 (0 -> 1 -> 2), it becomes 1 (0 -> 1). One increment is lost. This is why the buggy counter will often lag behind the actual number of clicks, especially with rapid clicking.</p>
            <p>The shared variable being contended for is `buggyCount` and the operations are the read-modify-write sequence.</p>

        <h3>The Corrected Counter Explained:</h3>
        <p>
            The "Increment (Corrected)" button uses a `processing` flag to prevent concurrent updates. This is a simple form of a <strong>lock</strong> or a <strong>mutex</strong> (mutual exclusion).
            <ol>
                <li>When a click occurs, it first checks if `processing` is `true`.</li>
                <li>If `processing` is `true`, it means an update is already in progress, so the new click is ignored (or could be queued, depending on desired behavior).</li>
                <li>If `processing` is `false`, it immediately sets `processing` to `true`. This "locks" the counter.</li>
                <li>It then proceeds with the read, delay (`setTimeout`), modify, and write operations.</li>
                <li>Crucially, <strong>after</strong> the update is complete (inside the `setTimeout` callback), it resets `processing` to `false`, "unlocking" the counter for the next update.</li>
            </ol>
            <p><strong>The solution:</strong> This ensures that only one increment operation can be active at a time. While one operation is `processing`, all subsequent clicks are blocked until the current operation completes and releases the lock. This guarantees that each increment reads the *latest* value, preventing the lost updates seen in the buggy version.</p>
            <p>The `processing` flag acts as a guard, ensuring that the critical section (reading `correctedCount`, incrementing it, and writing it back) is executed by only one operation at a time.</p>
    </div>

    <script>
        // --- Buggy Counter Logic ---
        let buggyCount = 0;
        const buggyCounterDisplay = document.getElementById('buggyCounter');
        const buggyButton = document.getElementById('buggyButton');

        function incrementBuggy() {
            // Simulate reading the current value
            const currentValue = buggyCount;

            // Simulate an asynchronous operation (e.g., a network request delay)
            // This is where the race condition becomes apparent
            setTimeout(() => {
                // By the time this runs, another increment might have started
                // and read the same 'currentValue' before this one wrote its result.
                buggyCount = currentValue + 1;
                buggyCounterDisplay.textContent = buggyCount;
                console.log(`Buggy: Read ${currentValue}, Wrote ${buggyCount}`);
            }, 100); // Small delay to make race condition more likely
        }

        buggyButton.addEventListener('click', incrementBuggy);

        // --- Corrected Counter Logic ---
        let correctedCount = 0;
        let processing = false; // Flag to prevent race conditions
        const correctedCounterDisplay = document.getElementById('correctedCounter');
        const correctedButton = document.getElementById('correctedButton');

        function incrementCorrected() {
            if (processing) {
                // If an operation is already in progress, ignore this click
                // or you could queue it, depending on desired behavior.
                console.warn('Corrected: Operation already in progress, ignoring click.');
                return;
            }

            processing = true; // Set flag to true, indicating an operation is starting

            // Simulate reading the current value
            const currentValue = correctedCount;

            // Simulate an asynchronous operation (e.g., a network request delay)
            setTimeout(() => {
                // This operation is guaranteed to be the only one modifying correctedCount
                // until 'processing' is set back to false.
                correctedCount = currentValue + 1;
                correctedCounterDisplay.textContent = correctedCount;
                console.log(`Corrected: Read ${currentValue}, Wrote ${correctedCount}`);

                processing = false; // Reset flag, allowing next operation to proceed
            }, 100); // Same delay as buggy for comparison
        }

        correctedButton.addEventListener('click', incrementCorrected);
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### How to use and observe the bug:

1.  **Save the code:** Save the entire content above as an `.html` file (e.g., `race_condition_demo.html`).
2.  **Open in browser:** Open the `race_condition_demo.html` file in your web browser.
3.  **Rapid Clicking:**
    *   **Buggy Counter:** Rapidly click the "Increment (Buggy)" button many times (e.g., 20-30 times in quick succession). You will notice that the displayed number is often significantly less than the number of clicks you performed. Check the browser's developer console (F12) to see the `Read X, Wrote Y` messages, which further illustrate when values are being overwritten.
    *   **Corrected Counter:** Do the same for the "Increment (Corrected)" button. Even with rapid clicking, the counter should accurately reflect the number of times you clicked (though some clicks might be ignored if they happen while `processing` is true, as indicated by the console warning). The key is that no *increments* are lost; if a click is processed, it correctly increments the counter.

This setup clearly shows how a race condition can lead to incorrect state and how a simple locking mechanism (like the `processing` flag) can resolve it by ensuring mutual exclusion for the critical section of code.

