        <h2>Understanding the Race Condition and its Fix</h2>

        <h3>The Problem: Race Condition</h3>
        <p>A race condition occurs when multiple parts of a program try to access and modify shared data simultaneously, and the final outcome depends on the unpredictable order in which these operations complete. In our "Buggy Counter" example, the shared data is the <code>count</code> variable.</p>
        <p>The "Increment" button triggers an asynchronous operation using <code>setTimeout</code>. While <code>setTimeout</code> is used here to simulate a short delay (like a network request or complex computation), the core issue is that the read, modify, and write operations on the shared <code>count</code> variable are not atomic (indivisible).</p>
