        const currentValue = buggyCount;
        <span class="highlight-bug">// MODIFY (calculate new value)</span>
        const newValue = currentValue + 1;
        <span class="highlight-bug">// WRITE buggyCount</span>
        buggyCount = newValue;
        document.getElementById('buggyCounterDisplay').textContent = buggyCount;
    }, 50); // Small delay to make race condition more apparent
});</code></pre>
        <p>The critical part is that <code>buggyCount</code> is read, then modified, then written back. If another click initiates this same sequence before the first one completes the write, they both operate on an outdated read, leading to lost updates.</p>

        <h3>The Fix: Using a Queue/Promise Chain (or Atomic Operations)</h3>
        <p>To prevent race conditions, we need to ensure that operations on shared data are performed atomically or in a controlled, sequential manner. In JavaScript's single-threaded event loop, we can achieve this by:</p>
        <ol>
            <li><strong>Using a Promise Chain:</strong> Each new operation waits for the previous one to complete before starting. This ensures that the <code>count</code> is always read at its most current state.</li>
            <li><strong>Disabling the button:</strong> While an operation is pending, disable the button to prevent new operations from starting. This is a simple UI-level fix, but doesn't solve the underlying data consistency issue if multiple sources could trigger updates.</li>
            <li><strong>Atomic Operations (not directly available for simple variables in JS):</strong> In multi-threaded environments, languages provide mechanisms like locks or mutexes to ensure only one thread can access a critical section of code at a time. JavaScript's single-threaded nature means we manage concurrency through the event loop, typically with Promises or async/await.</li>
        </ol>
        <p>Our "Fixed Counter" uses a promise chain. Each click adds a new operation to the chain. The <code>currentPromise</code> variable holds a promise that resolves when the *previous* increment operation is complete. The new operation then waits for <code>currentPromise</code> to resolve before executing its own <code>setTimeout</code> and then updates <code>currentPromise</code> with its own result.</p>

