        <p>The core problem lies in the "read-modify-write" cycle:</p>
        <ol>
            <li><strong>Read:</strong> An operation reads the current value of the state.</li>
            <li><strong>Modify:</strong> It performs some calculation based on that value.</li>
            <li><strong>Write:</strong> It writes the new value back to the state.</li>
        </ol>
        <p>If multiple asynchronous operations initiate this cycle at the same time, they might all <strong class="highlight-red">read the same initial value</strong> before any of them has finished writing back their updated value. When they eventually write, they overwrite each other's updates, leading to lost changes.</p>

        <h3>How it Happens in the Buggy Counter:</h3>
        <p>When you click the "Increment" button rapidly on the buggy counter:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Each click triggers an asynchronous update (simulated by <code>setTimeout</code>).</li>
            <li>Let's say the counter is at <code>0</code>.</li>
            <li>You click. Function A starts: <code>reads 0</code>.</li>
            <li>You click again *before* Function A writes. Function B starts: <code>reads 0</code>.</li>
            <li>Function A finishes its <code>setTimeout</code>, calculates <code>0 + 1 = 1</code>, and <code>writes 1</code>.</li>
            <li>Function B finishes its <code>setTimeout</code>, calculates <code>0 + 1 = 1</code>, and <code>writes 1</code>.</li>
            <li><strong class="highlight-red">Result:</strong> Two clicks, but the counter only shows <code>1</code> instead of <code>2</code>. One increment was lost!</li>
        </ul>
        <p>The <code>setTimeout</code> simulates a delay (e.g., fetching data from a server, or a complex client-side calculation) during which other operations can interleave and read stale data.</p>

        <h3>How the Fixed Counter Prevents It:</h3>
        <p>The fixed counter uses a simple but effective technique: <strong class="highlight-green">disabling the button</strong> while an asynchronous update is in progress. This acts as a <strong class="highlight-green">lock</strong> or <strong class="highlight-green">mutex</strong>:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>When an increment operation starts, the button is disabled.</li>
            <li>Subsequent clicks are ignored (or queued, depending on implementation, but here they are prevented from starting new operations).</li>
            <li>Once the asynchronous update (<code>setTimeout</code>) completes and the new value is written, the button is re-enabled.</li>
            <li>This ensures that only one "read-modify-write" cycle can be active at any given time, preventing other operations from reading stale data.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>While disabling the button is a common UI-level fix for this specific user interaction, more complex scenarios might require more sophisticated locking mechanisms (e.g., using a queue for pending operations, or state management libraries that handle asynchronous updates gracefully).</p>
    </div>

    <script>
        // --- Buggy Counter ---
        let buggyCounter = 0;
        const buggyCounterDisplay = document.getElementById('buggyCounterDisplay');
        const BUGGY_DELAY_MS = 150; // Simulate an async operation delay

        function incrementBuggyCounter() {
            // BUG: Reads the current counter value
            const currentValue = buggyCounter;

            // Simulate an asynchronous operation that takes some time
            setTimeout(() => {
                // BUG: Modifies and writes based on the value READ earlier,
                // which might be stale if another click happened in between.
                buggyCounter = currentValue + 1;
                buggyCounterDisplay.textContent = buggyCounter;
                console.log(`Buggy: Read ${currentValue}, Wrote ${buggyCounter}`);
            }, BUGGY_DELAY_MS);
        }

        function resetBuggyCounter() {
            buggyCounter = 0;
            buggyCounterDisplay.textContent = buggyCounter;
        }

        // --- Fixed Counter ---
        let fixedCounter = 0;
        const fixedCounterDisplay = document.getElementById('fixedCounterDisplay');
        const FIXED_DELAY_MS = 150; // Same delay for comparison
        let isUpdatingFixedCounter = false; // Our "lock" or "flag"

        function incrementFixedCounter() {
            if (isUpdatingFixedCounter) {
                // If an update is already in progress, ignore subsequent clicks
                // or you could queue them, depending on desired behavior.
                console.warn('Fixed: Update already in progress, ignoring click.');
                return;
            }

            isUpdatingFixedCounter = true; // Set the lock

            // Read, modify, and write are now "atomic" in terms of user interaction
            // because no other increment operation can start until this one finishes.
            const currentValue = fixedCounter; // Read

            setTimeout(() => {
                fixedCounter = currentValue + 1; // Modify
                fixedCounterDisplay.textContent = fixedCounter; // Write
                console.log(`Fixed: Read ${currentValue}, Wrote ${fixedCounter}`);
                isUpdatingFixedCounter = false; // Release the lock
            }, FIXED_DELAY_MS);
        }

        function resetFixedCounter() {
            if (isUpdatingFixedCounter) {
                console.warn('Fixed: Cannot reset while update is in progress.');
                return;
            }
            fixedCounter = 0;
            fixedCounterDisplay.textContent = fixedCounter;
        }
    </script>
