            for this in JavaScript is to use a <strong>queue</strong> or a <strong>lock/flag</strong> mechanism.
            Here, we use a simple flag (<code>isProcessing</code>) and a queue (<code>pendingIncrements</code>) to
            process increments one at a time.
        </p>
        <ol>
            <li>When an increment request comes in, it's added to a queue.</li>
            <li>If no operation is currently processing (<code>isProcessing</code> is false), we start processing
                the next item in the queue.
            </li>
            <li>The processing involves the same Read-Modify-Write cycle with a delay.</li>
            <li>Crucially, the <strong>Read</strong> always happens *after* the previous operation has completed its write.</li>
            <li>Once an operation completes, it sets <code>isProcessing</code> to false and immediately tries to
                process the next item in the queue.
            </li>
        </ol>
        <p>
            This effectively serializes the asynchronous updates to the shared state, preventing multiple operations
            from simultaneously operating on the same initial value. Each operation "sees" the most up-to-date
            state before performing its modification.
        </p>
        <div class="fixed-code">
            <pre><code>
let fixedCounter = 0;
let isProcessing = false;
const pendingIncrements = [];

function incrementFixed() {
    pendingIncrements.push(1); // Add an increment request to the queue
    processQueue();
}

function processQueue() {
    if (isProcessing || pendingIncrements.length === 0) {
        return; // Already processing or nothing in queue
    }

    isProcessing = true;
    pendingIncrements.shift(); // Take one request from the queue

    // READ the current value (this read happens *after* previous operations)
    const currentValue = fixedCounter;

    // Simulate async delay
    setTimeout(() => {
        // MODIFY based on the *latest* read
        const newValue = currentValue + 1;

        // WRITE the new value
        fixedCounter = newValue;
        document.getElementById('fixedCounterDisplay').textContent = fixedCounter;

        isProcessing = false; // Mark as done
        processQueue();       // Attempt to process next item in queue
    }, 100); // 100ms delay
}
            </code></pre>
